</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Heterotopic pancreas is a congenital anomaly in which pancreatic tissue is anatomically separate from the main gland. The most common locations of this displacement include the upper gastrointestinal tract—specifically, the stomach, duodenum, and proximal jejunum. Less common sites are the esophagus, ileum, Meckel diverticulum, biliary tree, mesentery, and spleen. Uncomplicated heterotopic pancreas is typically asymptomatic, with the lesion being discovered incidentally during an unrelated surgery, during an imaging examination, or at autopsy. The most common computed tomographic appearance of heterotopic pancreas is that of a small oval intramural mass with microlobulated margins and an endoluminal growth pattern. The attenuation and enhancement characteristics of these lesions parallel their histologic composition. Acinus-dominant lesions demonstrate avid homogeneous enhancement after intravenous contrast material administration, whereas duct-dominant lesions are hypovascular and heterogeneous. At magnetic resonance imaging, the heterotopic pancreas is isointense to the orthotopic pancreas, with characteristic T1 hyperintensity and early avid enhancement after intravenous gadolinium-based contrast material administration. Heterotopic pancreatic tissue has a rudimentary ductal system in which an orifice is sometimes visible at imaging as a central umbilication of the lesion. Complications of heterotopic pancreas include pancreatitis, pseudocyst formation, malignant degeneration, gastrointestinal bleeding, bowel obstruction, and intussusception. Certain complications may be erroneously diagnosed as malignancy. Paraduodenal pancreatitis is thought to be due to cystic degeneration of heterotopic pancreatic tissue in the medial wall of the duodenum. Recognizing the characteristic imaging features of heterotopic pancreas aids in differentiating it from cancer and thus in avoiding unnecessary surgery.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup> RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160091">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160091">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig1.jpeg" height="934" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Gastric heterotopic pancreas. Double-contrast upper gastrointestinal barium image shows an intramural mass (arrow) along the greater curvature of the gastric antrum. There is a central barium-filled pit, or umbilication (arrowhead). The location of and central umbilication in this lesion are characteristic of heterotopic pancreas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig2a.jpeg" height="787" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Gastric heterotopic pancreas. <b>(a)</b> Endoscopic image shows a submucosal mass (black arrow) within 6 cm of the pylorus (white arrow). The central depression (arrowhead) is the orifice for the rudimentary ductal system in heterotopic pancreatic tissue. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic ultrasonographic (US) image shows the mass (arrow) disrupting the hyperechoic submucosal layer of the gastric wall. The heterotopic pancreatic tissue is hypoechoic relative to the hyperechoic submucosa (white arrowhead) and isoechoic relative to the muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig2b.jpeg" height="787" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Gastric heterotopic pancreas. <b>(a)</b> Endoscopic image shows a submucosal mass (black arrow) within 6 cm of the pylorus (white arrow). The central depression (arrowhead) is the orifice for the rudimentary ductal system in heterotopic pancreatic tissue. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic ultrasonographic (US) image shows the mass (arrow) disrupting the hyperechoic submucosal layer of the gastric wall. The heterotopic pancreatic tissue is hypoechoic relative to the hyperechoic submucosa (white arrowhead) and isoechoic relative to the muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig3.jpeg" height="600" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Gastric heterotopic pancreas. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a small oval intramural gastric mass (arrow) with a predominantly endoluminal growth pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig4a.jpeg" height="666" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Gastric heterotopic pancreas in a 41-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced CT images show an oval intramural gastric mass (arrowhead) with homogeneous enhancement—similar to the enhancement of the normal pancreas (arrow in <b>a</b>). The mass is flat and has a long diameter–to–short diameter ratio higher than 1.4. It has an oval shape and endoluminal growth pattern, which are typical of heterotopic pancreatic lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig4b.jpeg" height="666" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Gastric heterotopic pancreas in a 41-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast material–enhanced CT images show an oval intramural gastric mass (arrowhead) with homogeneous enhancement—similar to the enhancement of the normal pancreas (arrow in <b>a</b>). The mass is flat and has a long diameter–to–short diameter ratio higher than 1.4. It has an oval shape and endoluminal growth pattern, which are typical of heterotopic pancreatic lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig5a.jpeg" height="600" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Jejunal heterotopic pancreas in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained during the arterial phase shows an avidly enhancing oval jejunal mass (arrow). The mass has a mixed endoluminal and exoluminal growth pattern, which is more common with heterotopic pancreatic lesions in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> Gross pathologic jejunum specimen shows a mass causing a bulge along the antimesenteric border. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding photomicrograph shows pancreatic acini (arrow) within the submucosa. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig5b.jpeg" height="591" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Jejunal heterotopic pancreas in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained during the arterial phase shows an avidly enhancing oval jejunal mass (arrow). The mass has a mixed endoluminal and exoluminal growth pattern, which is more common with heterotopic pancreatic lesions in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> Gross pathologic jejunum specimen shows a mass causing a bulge along the antimesenteric border. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding photomicrograph shows pancreatic acini (arrow) within the submucosa. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig5c.jpeg" height="591" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Jejunal heterotopic pancreas in a 27-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained during the arterial phase shows an avidly enhancing oval jejunal mass (arrow). The mass has a mixed endoluminal and exoluminal growth pattern, which is more common with heterotopic pancreatic lesions in the jejunum. <b>(b)</b> Gross pathologic jejunum specimen shows a mass causing a bulge along the antimesenteric border. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding photomicrograph shows pancreatic acini (arrow) within the submucosa. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig6a.jpeg" height="719" width="643" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Jejunal heterotopic pancreas. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b)</b>, and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images show a solid mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum. The mass is isointense to the normal pancreas (arrowheads) with all MR imaging sequences, with characteristic high signal intensity on the nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image and intense early enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig6b.jpeg" height="719" width="598" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Jejunal heterotopic pancreas. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b)</b>, and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images show a solid mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum. The mass is isointense to the normal pancreas (arrowheads) with all MR imaging sequences, with characteristic high signal intensity on the nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image and intense early enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig6c.jpeg" height="719" width="608" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Jejunal heterotopic pancreas. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b)</b>, and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images show a solid mass (arrow) in the proximal jejunum. The mass is isointense to the normal pancreas (arrowheads) with all MR imaging sequences, with characteristic high signal intensity on the nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image and intense early enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig7.jpeg" height="637" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Mesenteric heterotopic pancreas complicated by acute pancreatitis in a 43-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an elongated mass (white arrow) in the jejunal mesentery with surrounding fat stranding. The mass has a broad base intimately associated with a jejunal loop (white arrowhead) and tapers as it extends into the mesentery. Although the heterotopic tissue is anatomically separate from the orthotopic pancreas (black arrow), it has similar morphology and enhancement. A ductlike structure (black arrowhead) is seen paralleling the long axis of the mass. (Image courtesy of Aarti Sekhar, MD, Emory University, Atlanta, Ga.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig8a.jpeg" height="721" width="596" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the spleen. <b>(b–e)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> fat-saturated MR images and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images in the arterial <b>(d)</b> and equilibrium <b>(e)</b> phases show a solid, round, subcapsular splenic mass (arrow). The mass is hypointense on the T2-weighted image, slightly hyperintense on the nonenhanced T1-weighted image, and hypovascular relative to the spleen in the arterial phase, with progressive contrast material retention, in the equilibrium phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig8b.jpeg" height="721" width="632" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the spleen. <b>(b–e)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> fat-saturated MR images and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images in the arterial <b>(d)</b> and equilibrium <b>(e)</b> phases show a solid, round, subcapsular splenic mass (arrow). The mass is hypointense on the T2-weighted image, slightly hyperintense on the nonenhanced T1-weighted image, and hypovascular relative to the spleen in the arterial phase, with progressive contrast material retention, in the equilibrium phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig8c.jpeg" height="721" width="622" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the spleen. <b>(b–e)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> fat-saturated MR images and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images in the arterial <b>(d)</b> and equilibrium <b>(e)</b> phases show a solid, round, subcapsular splenic mass (arrow). The mass is hypointense on the T2-weighted image, slightly hyperintense on the nonenhanced T1-weighted image, and hypovascular relative to the spleen in the arterial phase, with progressive contrast material retention, in the equilibrium phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig8d.jpeg" height="662" width="658" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the spleen. <b>(b–e)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> fat-saturated MR images and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images in the arterial <b>(d)</b> and equilibrium <b>(e)</b> phases show a solid, round, subcapsular splenic mass (arrow). The mass is hypointense on the T2-weighted image, slightly hyperintense on the nonenhanced T1-weighted image, and hypovascular relative to the spleen in the arterial phase, with progressive contrast material retention, in the equilibrium phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig8e.jpeg" height="662" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. Splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 67-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the spleen. <b>(b–e)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> fat-saturated MR images and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images in the arterial <b>(d)</b> and equilibrium <b>(e)</b> phases show a solid, round, subcapsular splenic mass (arrow). The mass is hypointense on the T2-weighted image, slightly hyperintense on the nonenhanced T1-weighted image, and hypovascular relative to the spleen in the arterial phase, with progressive contrast material retention, in the equilibrium phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig9a.jpeg" height="1200" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Cystadenocarcinoma in splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 57-year-old woman. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b)</b>, and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images show a multilocular cystic mass (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) in the spleen (white arrow in <b>a</b>) and separate from the pancreas (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). The fluid in the cystic mass has high signal intensity on the fat-saturated nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image owing to the mucin content. There is a central enhancing soft-tissue component (arrowhead in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig9b.jpeg" height="1256" width="1678" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Cystadenocarcinoma in splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 57-year-old woman. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b)</b>, and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images show a multilocular cystic mass (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) in the spleen (white arrow in <b>a</b>) and separate from the pancreas (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). The fluid in the cystic mass has high signal intensity on the fat-saturated nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image owing to the mucin content. There is a central enhancing soft-tissue component (arrowhead in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig9c.jpeg" height="1256" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Cystadenocarcinoma in splenic heterotopic pancreas in a 57-year-old woman. Axial T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b)</b>, and contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images show a multilocular cystic mass (black arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) in the spleen (white arrow in <b>a</b>) and separate from the pancreas (arrowheads in <b>b</b>). The fluid in the cystic mass has high signal intensity on the fat-saturated nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image owing to the mucin content. There is a central enhancing soft-tissue component (arrowhead in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig10.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Jejunal pancreatic heterotopia complicated by acute pancreatitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an oval intramural mass (arrowhead) in the jejunum. The mass has enhancement similar to that of the normal pancreatic head and is surrounded by inflammatory edema and a thickened jejunal wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig11a.jpeg" height="680" width="907" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Gastric pancreatic heterotopia complicated by pseudocyst formation in a 38-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show an intramural mass (arrow) along the greater curvature of the gastric antrum. Similar to the normal pancreatic tissue, the mass is intensely enhancing and contains multiple small internal cystic areas. Also note the hyperenhancement of the overlying gastric mucosa (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) and the endoluminal growth pattern of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig11b.jpeg" height="680" width="868" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Gastric pancreatic heterotopia complicated by pseudocyst formation in a 38-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show an intramural mass (arrow) along the greater curvature of the gastric antrum. Similar to the normal pancreatic tissue, the mass is intensely enhancing and contains multiple small internal cystic areas. Also note the hyperenhancement of the overlying gastric mucosa (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) and the endoluminal growth pattern of the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig12a.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Cystadenocarcinoma in gastric heterotopic pancreas in a 68-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT <b>(a)</b> and axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(b)</b> images show a multilocular mixed cystic-solid mass arising from the greater curvature of the stomach (arrow in <b>a</b>) and extending into the lesser sac. The mass has thick enhancing septa (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) and is separate from the normal pancreatic tissue. The PET/CT image shows increased metabolic activity of the solid component (arrowhead). Hypermetabolic periaortic adenopathy (arrow in <b>b</b>) also is present. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy revealed a mural lesion without mucosal involvement. Biopsy revealed cystadenocarcinoma of pancreatic origin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig12b.jpeg" height="788" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Cystadenocarcinoma in gastric heterotopic pancreas in a 68-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT <b>(a)</b> and axial fused positron emission tomographic (PET)/CT <b>(b)</b> images show a multilocular mixed cystic-solid mass arising from the greater curvature of the stomach (arrow in <b>a</b>) and extending into the lesser sac. The mass has thick enhancing septa (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) and is separate from the normal pancreatic tissue. The PET/CT image shows increased metabolic activity of the solid component (arrowhead). Hypermetabolic periaortic adenopathy (arrow in <b>b</b>) also is present. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy revealed a mural lesion without mucosal involvement. Biopsy revealed cystadenocarcinoma of pancreatic origin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig13a.jpeg" height="666" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 50-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a hypovascular sheetlike mass (white arrowhead) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove without involvement of the adjacent pancreatic head (black arrow). There is associated wall thickening and luminal narrowing of the duodenum (white arrow in <b>b</b>). Note the displacement—rather than encasement—of nearby vessels (black arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig13b.jpeg" height="666" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 50-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a hypovascular sheetlike mass (white arrowhead) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove without involvement of the adjacent pancreatic head (black arrow). There is associated wall thickening and luminal narrowing of the duodenum (white arrow in <b>b</b>). Note the displacement—rather than encasement—of nearby vessels (black arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig14a.jpeg" height="1332" width="1776" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows cysts (arrowhead) along the medial wall of the duodenum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple cysts (arrowheads) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove, which are causing luminal narrowing of the second portion of the duodenum (white arrow). With this pure form of groove pancreatitis, the pancreatic head (black arrow) is not involved. Cysts in the groove or medial duodenal wall are a specific finding of groove pancreatitis and are rarely seen with pancreatic adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig14b.jpeg" height="1332" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image shows cysts (arrowhead) along the medial wall of the duodenum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple cysts (arrowheads) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove, which are causing luminal narrowing of the second portion of the duodenum (white arrow). With this pure form of groove pancreatitis, the pancreatic head (black arrow) is not involved. Cysts in the groove or medial duodenal wall are a specific finding of groove pancreatitis and are rarely seen with pancreatic adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig15a.jpeg" height="666" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue and cystic change in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow), as well as wall thickening of the adjacent duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image best shows the cysts (arrowhead) in the groove. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image enables the best differentiation of the sheetlike mass (white arrow) in the groove from the normal pancreatic head (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted arterial phase MR image best demonstrates the hyperenhancement and thickening of the duodenal wall (arrowhead) and shows the hypovascular nature of the fibrous mass (arrow) in the groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig15b.jpeg" height="666" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue and cystic change in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow), as well as wall thickening of the adjacent duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image best shows the cysts (arrowhead) in the groove. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image enables the best differentiation of the sheetlike mass (white arrow) in the groove from the normal pancreatic head (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted arterial phase MR image best demonstrates the hyperenhancement and thickening of the duodenal wall (arrowhead) and shows the hypovascular nature of the fibrous mass (arrow) in the groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig15c.jpeg" height="666" width="884" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue and cystic change in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow), as well as wall thickening of the adjacent duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image best shows the cysts (arrowhead) in the groove. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image enables the best differentiation of the sheetlike mass (white arrow) in the groove from the normal pancreatic head (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted arterial phase MR image best demonstrates the hyperenhancement and thickening of the duodenal wall (arrowhead) and shows the hypovascular nature of the fibrous mass (arrow) in the groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig15d.jpeg" height="666" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue and cystic change in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow), as well as wall thickening of the adjacent duodenum (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image best shows the cysts (arrowhead) in the groove. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image enables the best differentiation of the sheetlike mass (white arrow) in the groove from the normal pancreatic head (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted arterial phase MR image best demonstrates the hyperenhancement and thickening of the duodenal wall (arrowhead) and shows the hypovascular nature of the fibrous mass (arrow) in the groove.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig16a.jpeg" height="841" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a sheetlike hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove, with thickening and cystic change (black arrowhead) of the adjacent medial wall of the duodenum (white arrowhead). Note the normal homogeneous enhancement of the pancreatic head and normal-caliber common bile duct. <b>(b)</b> Static upper gastrointestinal image shows luminal narrowing (arrow) of the second portion of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig16b.jpeg" height="841" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a sheetlike hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove, with thickening and cystic change (black arrowhead) of the adjacent medial wall of the duodenum (white arrowhead). Note the normal homogeneous enhancement of the pancreatic head and normal-caliber common bile duct. <b>(b)</b> Static upper gastrointestinal image shows luminal narrowing (arrow) of the second portion of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig17.jpeg" height="637" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 60-year-old woman. Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple small cysts (arrow) in the medial wall of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig18a.jpeg" height="667" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 49-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows wall thickening (white arrowhead) of the second portion of the duodenum and a complex cystic lesion (black arrowhead) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image best shows the sheetlike mass (arrow) in the groove and separate from the pancreatic head (arrowhead) and duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows hyperenhancement of the thickened duodenal wall (white arrowhead). Also note the normal-caliber common bile duct (black arrowhead). The fact that the mass in the groove is difficult to differentiate from the pancreatic head during this phase of contrast enhancement further emphasizes the importance of nonenhanced T1-weighted MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig18b.jpeg" height="667" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 49-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows wall thickening (white arrowhead) of the second portion of the duodenum and a complex cystic lesion (black arrowhead) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image best shows the sheetlike mass (arrow) in the groove and separate from the pancreatic head (arrowhead) and duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows hyperenhancement of the thickened duodenal wall (white arrowhead). Also note the normal-caliber common bile duct (black arrowhead). The fact that the mass in the groove is difficult to differentiate from the pancreatic head during this phase of contrast enhancement further emphasizes the importance of nonenhanced T1-weighted MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig18c.jpeg" height="674" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis in a 49-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows wall thickening (white arrowhead) of the second portion of the duodenum and a complex cystic lesion (black arrowhead) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image best shows the sheetlike mass (arrow) in the groove and separate from the pancreatic head (arrowhead) and duodenum. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows hyperenhancement of the thickened duodenal wall (white arrowhead). Also note the normal-caliber common bile duct (black arrowhead). The fact that the mass in the groove is difficult to differentiate from the pancreatic head during this phase of contrast enhancement further emphasizes the importance of nonenhanced T1-weighted MR imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig19a.jpeg" height="737" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a mildly hyperintense sheetlike mass (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection MR cholangiopancreatographic image shows smooth tapered stenosis of the common bile duct with upstream biliary dilatation, and focal stenosis (arrowhead) of the main pancreatic duct, with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct and side branches. The widened space (arrow) between the duodenal lumen and common bile duct in <b>b</b> is a result of the mass in the groove and duodenal wall thickening. Although much of the pancreas is spared with groove pancreatitis, chronic changes resulting from long-standing stenosis in the pancreatic head can be seen. Note the smooth tapered narrowing of the common bile duct in contrast to the abrupt, irregular, shouldering stenosis that is typically seen with pancreatic adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160091/asset/images/large/rg.2017160091.fig19b.jpeg" height="737" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Paraduodenal pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a mildly hyperintense sheetlike mass (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection MR cholangiopancreatographic image shows smooth tapered stenosis of the common bile duct with upstream biliary dilatation, and focal stenosis (arrowhead) of the main pancreatic duct, with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct and side branches. The widened space (arrow) between the duodenal lumen and common bile duct in <b>b</b> is a result of the mass in the groove and duodenal wall thickening. Although much of the pancreas is spared with groove pancreatitis, chronic changes resulting from long-standing stenosis in the pancreatic head can be seen. Note the smooth tapered narrowing of the common bile duct in contrast to the abrupt, irregular, shouldering stenosis that is typically seen with pancreatic adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160091&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kung JW, Brown A, Kruskal JB, Goldsmith JD, Pedrosa I. Heterotopic pancreas: typical and atypical imaging findings. <em>Clin Radiol</em> 2010;65(5):403–407.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.crad.2010.01.005">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20380941/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Heterotopic+pancreas%3A+typical+and+atypical+imaging+findings&amp;author=JW+Kung&amp;author=A+Brown&amp;author=JB+Kruskal&amp;author=JD+Goldsmith&amp;author=I+Pedrosa&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=Clin+Radiol&amp;pages=403-407&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.crad.2010.01.005&amp;pmid=20380941">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Wei R, Wang QB, Chen QH, Liu JS, Zhang B. Upper gastrointestinal tract heterotopic pancreas: findings from CT and endoscopic imaging with histopathologic correlation. <em>Clin Imaging</em> 2011;35(5):353–359.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.clinimag.2010.10.001">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21872124/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Upper+gastrointestinal+tract+heterotopic+pancreas%3A+findin